<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-298-011  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 298 011.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Jan 23 1989 n204 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MIS finds IBM more enterprising: IBM's increased ability to meetMIS's demand for enterprise solutions fuels Big Blue's recordearnings. (management information systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Colonna, Jerome D.; Leibs, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM realized record revenue and earnings in 1988 partly because ofthe surprising success of the AS-400.andP;  The midrange systems serieshas shipped more than 30,000 units since its Jun 1988introduction.andP;  More important for the future, however, was theshipping of another series of products: the ES-3090 S and MVS-ESA.andO;These first concrete products of IBM's Enterprise SystemsArchitecture (ESA) significantly contributed to the company'srecord revenue.andP;  ESA represents IBM's concurrent realignment inthe way it sells to MIS.andP;  The company is targeting the market'sgrowing, enterprise-wide computing needs.andP;  All future IBM productswill reflect this new marketing tactic.andP;  All new strategicproducts will include the name 'enterprise' in them to indicatethe extended memory and storage addressing that is the hallmark ofESA.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM Enterprise System-3090 S (Mainframe computer)MVS-ESA (Operating system) (marketing)IBM AS-400 (Minicomputer) (marketing).andO;Topic:     RevenueMarketing StrategyNew Product.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   (IBM sales 1983-1988). (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>